docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:56:- Source extracts for the 2026-07-03_224536 review: `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §11.4 defines `/auth/me/` profile + roles + teams + permissions; its closing implementation rule says React uses `available_actions` for UX while Django remains authoritative. `docs/source/implementation-roadmap.md` §10.6 says UI navigation must be role-aware and backend rejects unauthorized API calls. `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §13.1 includes role codes `it_head`, `internal_auditor`, `management_viewer`, and others that the frontend bridge must handle explicitly or neutrally.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:57:- 002EX must consume the 002E/002E2 bridge: no tracer screen before backend login and `/auth/me/`; no demo-auth bypass for smoke evidence; empty-permission or unmapped-role sessions must not see tracer actions or inherited auditor/admin/borrower affordances.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:58:- 002EY should make Playwright prove the same production/default auth path. Its login flow must hit the dev Django server and should include negative browser checks that missing/revoked sessions land on staff login and zero-permission/unmapped backend roles cannot expose tracer routes/actions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:59:- 002E2 completed the frontend role bridge hardening: unmapped backend roles and zero-permission seeded roles such as `it_head` and `management_viewer` now map to neutral frontend role `backend_staff`, preserve backend `roleName`/`roleCodes`/team display, and receive no prototype permissions unless canonical backend permissions map explicitly. Dashboard/profile/header branches no longer grant auditor/admin/borrower affordances to this neutral role; the header Settings shortcut is hidden unless `view_settings` is granted.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:60:- 002EX completed the first real integration proof: minimal `tracer` Django app, one migration, session-bound `/api/v1/tracer/...` endpoints, service-layer transition guards, one audit log and one workflow event per transition, a staff-shell Tracer screen, and a narrow `tracer.lifecycle.run` permission bridge. Source extracts used: `api-contracts.md` §3 requires backend-enforced workflow, explicit action endpoints, auditability, versioned `/api/v1/`, and standard envelopes; `data-model.md` §26.1-26.2 defines append-only audit logs and workflow events. Browser screenshots remain deferred to 002EY because this sandbox blocked localhost binding with `EPERM`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:61:- 002F completed the role-aware shell hardening: `PAGE_PERMISSIONS` and `resolveNavigationAttempt()` now live in `sfpcl-lms/src/services/navigationPermissions.ts`, `Sidebar.tsx` exports the canonical staff nav table for parity tests, and `App.tsx` uses the shared guard helper. Frontend tests assert every non-dashboard staff nav item is gated by the same prototype permission as its page, blocked navigation returns to Dashboard with `blockedPage`, `tracer.lifecycle.run` maps only to `run_tracer`, and unknown/empty-role current-user responses stay neutral. The 002EY `auth-negative` Playwright spec was extended for zero-permission, tracer-only, and invalid stored-session restore checks; local browser execution remained blocked by sandbox localhost `EPERM`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:62:- 002FL completed the frontend lint baseline: `npm run lint` runs `eslint src` with pinned approved packages (`eslint`, `typescript-eslint`, `eslint-plugin-react-hooks`, `eslint-plugin-react-refresh`) and a flat config. The baseline preserves the existing prototype design/permissions and fixes only lint-safe hook dependency, switch-case scope, and `prefer-const` findings. The protected `.ralph/config.yaml` lint gate still needs owner/operator flip to `quality_gates.lint: true`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:65:  - 002F2 must replace the shallow 002F navigation visibility test with behavior-level coverage of the actual Sidebar visibility path and route guard for zero-permission, tracer-only, unknown-role, and future admin-management navigation.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:67:- For 002G: build admin user/role management on the existing identity catalogue and `/auth/me/` serialization shape. Use `manage_users` as the explicit permission gate, standard envelopes/pagination, session-bound auth, existing `AuditLog`, and frontend navigation/page guard tests through the 002F shared navigation contract. Do not create free-text roles, teams, or permissions; bind only existing catalogue rows. Suspending a user must revoke active sessions; last-system-admin lock-out should be recorded in `ASSUMPTIONS.md` if source-doc-silent.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:69:- 002F2 completed the shallow Sidebar visibility corrective slice: `visibleStaffNavItems()` now lives in `sfpcl-lms/src/services/navigationPermissions.ts`, `Sidebar` consumes it with `allNavItems`, and vitest covers the actual visibility path plus direct route guard behavior for every protected item, zero-permission backend sessions, unknown/empty-role backend sessions, and tracer-only sessions. `tracer.lifecycle.run` still maps only to `run_tracer` and unlocks only Dashboard + Tracer.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:71:- 002G completed admin user-management shell: backend routes under `/api/v1/admin/users/` list/detail users with the `/auth/me/` `roles[{role_code, role_name}]` and `teams[{team_code, team_name}]` shape, bind only existing active `Role`/`Team` rows, set status to `active`/`suspended`, audit role/team/status changes, and revoke active sessions when a user is suspended. Backend gate requires a session-bound active access token plus at least one canonical user-admin permission (`users.user.create`, `users.user.update`, `users.user.disable`); frontend maps those to prototype `manage_users` and adds `admin-users` to `allNavItems`, `PAGE_PERMISSIONS`, and the app route guard. A-014 records the source-silent last active `system_admin` guard: role/status changes that would leave zero active `system_admin` users return `400 VALIDATION_ERROR`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:72:- For 002H: keep the workflow guard foundation domain-neutral. A shared backend transition guard may define from-state, to-state, required permission, action code, and audit/workflow-event metadata, but must not encode loan eligibility, sanction authority, money amounts, or document-completeness rules. Migrate only the existing tracer transition proof to the shared guard and preserve its public endpoint behavior and `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION` / `403 PERMISSION_DENIED` envelopes.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:73:- For 002I: build only a domain-neutral object-level permission helper/test harness. It should accept explicit actor permissions/team codes plus object owner/team facts, allow owner or matching team access, deny missing module permission as `PERMISSION_DENIED`, deny mismatched or unknown object scope as object access denied, and avoid adding public endpoints or querying future loan/member/application tables.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:74:- 002H completed the shared workflow guard foundation. `sfpcl_credit/workflows/guard.py` defines domain-neutral transition definitions/results plus typed errors for unknown action, missing permission, and invalid state. Tracer services now pass explicit actor permission codes into the shared guard for lifecycle actions while preserving existing tracer URLs, success payloads, `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`, `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION`, audit logs, and workflow events. No schema change.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:75:- Architecture review 2026-07-04_135247 found one corrective follow-up before 002I: 002G's backend admin gate treats any one of `users.user.create`, `users.user.update`, or `users.user.disable` as full user-management authority. Source extract: `auth-permissions.md` §12.1 defines `users.user.read`, `users.user.create`, `users.user.update`, and `users.user.disable` as distinct risk-rated permissions; §15.12 grants System Administrator create/update/disable plus role/config permissions; §19 maps `/settings/users` to `users.user.read`. Corrective slice `002G2` must add action-specific backend permission tests and preserve existing system-admin access.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:76:- 002G2 completed the action-aware admin permission gate. `admin_views._authenticated_admin` now takes per-action required permission code sets from `admin_users`: list/detail read needs `users.user.read` OR any write user-admin permission (read fallback per A-015 because seeded `system_admin` lacks `users.user.read`); role assignment and team add/remove need `users.user.update`; suspend needs `users.user.disable`; restore-to-active needs `users.user.update`. `set_status` authorises after parsing the target status (`status_permission_codes`) so suspend and restore are gated differently; check order is `401`→`403`→`400`/`404`, and forbidden partial-permission writes create no `AuditLog` and revoke no session. The now-unused `has_manage_users_permission` helper was removed (`MANAGE_USERS_PERMISSION_CODES` is retained as the read fallback + frontend `manage_users` mapping set). Regression tests cover create-only, update-only, disable-only, and read-only partial roles plus the negative audit/session side effects. No schema change; frontend nav/route unchanged.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:77:- For 002J: create a test-only API contract assertion harness. Use existing endpoints as fixtures: `/auth/me/` for success envelope, admin users for pagination and `403`, tracer invalid state for `409`, and an internal sample for `available_actions` shape. Do not add public endpoints or production dependencies.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:82:- Guardrails tested: positive amounts only; invalid state transitions return `409 INVALID_STATE_TRANSITION`; missing bearer auth returns `401 AUTH_REQUIRED`; revoked access sessions return `401 INVALID_TOKEN`; authenticated users without `tracer.lifecycle.run` return `403 PERMISSION_DENIED`; zero-permission/unmapped frontend roles do not map tracer permissions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:86:- Permission naming convention: §11 (verbs in §11.1); full permission catalogue by module: §12.1–12.13 (auth/user-admin, members, KYC, applications, credit assessment, approvals, documentation, security, SAP/finance, monitoring/default, closure, compliance, reports/audit/config).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:88:- Role-to-permission matrix: §14.1 (high level), §15.1–15.12 (per-role detail — the seed data source).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:90:- Frontend already has a prototype permission model in `sfpcl-lms/src/contexts/RoleContext.tsx` (union `Permission`, `ROLE_PERMISSIONS`) — the seeded backend catalogue is the source of truth; the frontend union gets reconciled in 002D/002E.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:91:- ASSUMPTION made during 2026-07-02 repair (reconcile in this slice): prototype calls `can('export')`/`can('export_reports')`/`can('view_loans')` were mapped to existing `export_registers`/`view_loan_accounts` permissions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:96:- Session policy: §8.2. Sensitive re-auth flow: §6.5 (later slice).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:97:- Data model tables: §10.1–10.8 (`users`, `roles`, `permissions`, `role_permissions`, `teams`, `user_team_memberships`, `user_sessions`, `sensitive_access_logs`).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:98:- Source API contract §11.4 defines `/api/v1/auth/me/` as current user profile, roles, teams, and permissions. API conventions require `Authorization: Bearer <access_token>` for protected APIs and standard success/error envelopes with `meta.request_id`, `meta.timestamp`, and `meta.api_version`.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:102:- Current code before 002C2 has two production success helpers: `sfpcl_credit/ops.py` for health (missing `api_version`) and `sfpcl_credit/identity/views.py` for auth (includes `api_version`).
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:103:- `docs/source/technical-architecture.md` §13.1 says Django views should not contain complex workflow orchestration; multi-entity operations, permissions, calculations, and audit logs belong in explicit service classes/functions.
docs/working/digests/epic-002-platform-auth.md:105:- Keep endpoint URLs and auth behavior unchanged: PyJWT HS256, token lifetimes, JWT claims, refresh rotation, replay rejection, logout revocation, inactive-user rejection, and auth audit events.
