docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:1:# Slice 002I: Object-Level Permission Test Harness
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:8:Epic file: `docs/epics/002-platform-auth-shell.md`
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:11:Add a narrow backend object-level permission harness that future member/application/loan slices can reuse in tests before real object-assignment tables arrive.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:14:Future workflow APIs can prove "has module permission" is not enough: object/team assignment scope must be checked independently and denied with the standard envelope when the user is outside scope.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:23:- docs/source/auth-permissions.md
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:28:- sfpcl-lms/src/pages/auth/LoginScreen.tsx
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:40:1. Add a small domain-neutral permission helper module (for example under `sfpcl_credit/identity/modules/`) that evaluates an actor's access to an object using explicit inputs only: actor user id, actor team codes, required canonical permission code, object owner user id, object team code, and an optional `allow_global` flag.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:42:3. Add a thin test-only fixture or service-level test harness around the helper; do not add public production endpoints solely for the harness.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:43:4. Reuse `auth_service.effective_permission_codes()` for the module-permission side, and `auth_service.team_payload()` / `User.team_codes()` shape for team membership inputs.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:44:5. Keep object access separate from 002H's workflow transition guard: 002H checks action/state/permission, while 002I checks whether the actor is allowed to touch the specific object after permission passes.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:45:6. Start only after 002G2 closes the admin action-permission granularity finding. This helper must accept the exact required canonical permission from the caller and must not collapse distinct permissions into a broad UI/prototype permission such as `manage_users`.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:48:- Reuse existing symbols (all confirmed present): `auth_service.effective_permission_codes(user)` returns the sorted canonical codes for the active primary role; `User.team_codes()` (`sfpcl_credit/identity/models.py:107`) returns the actor's active team codes; `auth_service.team_payload(user)` returns `[{team_code, team_name}]`.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:49:- Follow the 002G2 pattern for action-specific gating: `admin_users.user_has_action_permission(user, required_codes)` intersects a required-code set with `effective_permission_codes` — the object helper's module-permission side should behave the same way (accept an explicit required code, not a role name).
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:50:- Error envelope: use `sfpcl_credit/api.error_response(request, 403, "PERMISSION_DENIED", ...)` for the missing-permission path if any thin test endpoint is added; the helper itself should return a typed result/reason code and let callers translate (mirrors `workflows/guard.py` typed errors from 002H).
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:59:Apply `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` object/team scope language:
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:61:- If the actor lacks the required canonical permission, deny with `PERMISSION_DENIED`.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:62:- If the actor has the module permission but does not own the object, is not on the object's team, and no explicit global override is supplied, deny as object access denied.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:70:- The helper accepts only explicit object-scope facts supplied by callers.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:71:- Missing object owner/team facts default to deny unless `allow_global` is true and the actor has the required permission.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:72:- The helper must make the deny reason test-visible (`missing_permission`, `owner_mismatch`, `team_mismatch`, or `scope_unknown`) so future endpoint tests can assert the correct error path.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:73:- Use the 002H boundary explicitly: call the object-scope helper after module permission is known and before future workflow transitions are executed. Do not make the object helper call `evaluate_transition()` or know workflow state names.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:75:- Source trace to use in the review packet: `auth-permissions.md` §3/§3.1 says the backend enforces role, team/assignment, object-level, and workflow-state checks; `technical-architecture.md` §7.2 says permissions and services are separate backend layers; `api-contracts.md` §44 says frontend action availability is only UX and backend remains authoritative.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:76:- Regression trace from 002G2: canonical permission codes remain action-specific on the backend; object-scope checks must not use the frontend's coarse prototype permission names as authorization inputs.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:79:Unit/service/API/permission tests plus frontend tests where UI is touched.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:80:- Backend TDD: actor with required permission and object owner id matches -> allowed.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:81:- Backend TDD: actor with required permission and active team membership matching the object team -> allowed.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:82:- Backend TDD: actor without the required canonical permission -> denied as missing permission.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:83:- Backend TDD: actor with permission but mismatched owner/team -> denied as object access denied.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:84:- Backend TDD: unknown/missing object scope -> denied unless an explicit global override is passed.
docs/slices/002I-object-level-permission-test-harness.md:85:- Regression: this helper must not alter existing `/auth/me/`, admin user-management, or tracer permission behavior.
